# Why Are Veterans Homeless in America? An In-Depth Analysis

Homelessness among veterans in the United States has been a persistent and complex social issue for over three decades. Despite the nation's efforts to honor and support those who have served in the armed forces, a significant number of veterans continue to experience homelessness. This report provides a detailed, evidence-based examination of the causes and risk factors contributing to veteran homelessness in America. Drawing from systematic reviews, government data, and scholarly research, it offers a comprehensive understanding of why veterans become homeless, supported by relevant statistics and insights into the interplay of various contributing factors.

---

## Overview of Veteran Homelessness in America

Veterans are disproportionately represented among the homeless population in the U.S. Although veterans constitute approximately 9.7% of the total U.S. population, they account for about 12.3% of all homeless adults ([Tsai & Rosenheck, 2015](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25595171/)). According to the National Alliance to End Homelessness, point-in-time counts in January 2019 identified 37,085 homeless veterans nationwide, marking a significant decrease of 43.3% since 2011, yet veterans remain overrepresented ([National Alliance to End Homelessness, 2015](https://endhomelessness.org/resource/veteran-homelessness/)).

Homeless veterans tend to be older, better educated, more likely to be male, and more often married or previously married compared to nonveteran homeless adults. Despite these demographic differences, veterans face unique and overlapping challenges that increase their risk of homelessness.

---

## Primary Risk Factors for Veteran Homelessness

### 1. Substance Use Disorders

The most consistently identified and strongest risk factor for veteran homelessness is substance use disorder (SUD), including alcohol and drug abuse. Studies spanning over two decades consistently show that veterans experiencing homelessness frequently struggle with substance abuse, which exacerbates housing instability ([Tsai & Rosenheck, 2015](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25595171/); [Veteran Addiction, n.d.](https://veteranaddiction.org/rehab-guide/homeless-veterans/)).

Substance use often serves as a coping mechanism for underlying mental health issues, including PTSD and other psychiatric disorders. Veterans with opioid use disorder, for example, have a prevalence of homelessness ten times higher than the general veteran population ([National Alliance to End Homelessness, 2015](https://endhomelessness.org/resource/veteran-homelessness/)).

### 2. Mental Illness

Mental health disorders, including severe psychiatric conditions such as schizophrenia, bipolar disorder, and depression, are significant contributors to homelessness among veterans. PTSD, while a focus of many studies, does not appear to be a uniquely strong predictor compared to other mental illnesses but often co-occurs with substance use disorders, compounding the risk ([Tsai & Rosenheck, 2015](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25595171/); [Veteran Addiction, n.d.](https://veteranaddiction.org/rehab-guide/homeless-veterans/)).

The co-occurrence of mental illness and substance abuse—often referred to as dual diagnosis—is prevalent among homeless veterans, making treatment and housing stability more challenging ([Tsai & Rosenheck, 2015](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25595171/)).

### 3. Low Income and Economic Instability

Poverty and low income are pervasive risk factors for homelessness across all populations, including veterans. Studies identify low military pay grade, unemployment, and financial mismanagement as key contributors to housing instability ([Tsai & Rosenheck, 2015](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25595171/); [Veteran Addiction, n.d.](https://veteranaddiction.org/rehab-guide/homeless-veterans/)).

Veterans often face challenges transitioning to civilian employment, with some cohorts experiencing unemployment rates as high as 30.2% among younger veterans aged 18-24 ([The Military Wallet, 2021](https://themilitarywallet.com/homeless-veterans-in-america/)). Additionally, over 968,000 veterans lived in poverty in recent years, and many have lost homes due to foreclosure ([The Military Wallet, 2021](https://themilitarywallet.com/homeless-veterans-in-america/)).

### 4. Social Isolation and Lack of Support Networks

Social isolation, including lack of family or community support, is another important risk factor. Veterans who are unmarried or who experience social isolation after military discharge are more vulnerable to homelessness ([Tsai & Rosenheck, 2015](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25595171/)).

The transition from military to civilian life can be difficult, especially for those without strong social support or transferable employment skills. This isolation can exacerbate mental health issues and increase the risk of substance abuse ([National Alliance to End Homelessness, 2015](https://endhomelessness.org/resource/veteran-homelessness/)).

### 5. Adverse Childhood Experiences and Past Incarceration

Some studies indicate that adverse childhood experiences (ACEs), including physical or sexual abuse and foster care placement, as well as histories of incarceration, contribute to the risk of homelessness among veterans ([Tsai & Rosenheck, 2015](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25595171/)).

These factors often compound with other vulnerabilities, making it difficult for affected veterans to maintain stable housing.

### 6. Military Service-Related Factors

Certain military-specific factors also increase homelessness risk:

- **Problematic Military Discharges:** Veterans with less-than-honorable discharges often face barriers to accessing VA benefits and services, increasing their risk ([Tsai & Rosenheck, 2015](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25595171/)).

- **Low Military Pay Grade:** Lower rank and pay correlate with economic hardship post-service.

- **Combat Exposure and PTSD:** While combat exposure and PTSD are prevalent among veterans, research suggests they do not independently increase homelessness risk as strongly as other factors, possibly due to targeted VA services ([Tsai & Rosenheck, 2015](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25595171/)).

---

## Demographic and Historical Context

Veteran homelessness is not a new phenomenon. Historical data show that homeless veterans have been part of the homeless population since at least the Reconstruction Era. For example, in 1934, there were as many as 250,000 homeless veterans in the U.S. ([Wikipedia, n.d.](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homeless_veterans_in_the_United_States)).

Currently, Vietnam veterans constitute a significant portion of the homeless veteran population, with 47% of homeless veterans being from this cohort ([The Military Wallet, 2021](https://themilitarywallet.com/homeless-veterans-in-america/)). Younger veterans from recent conflicts such as Iraq and Afghanistan make up a smaller but growing percentage.

